{{news release|1=article|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox person |name= Elena Reynaga |image = Elena Reynaga.jpg |caption = |birth_name = Elena Eva Reynaga |birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1953|07|28}} |birth_place = [[Jujuy]], Argentina |residence = |occupation = |known_for = [[Women human rights defenders|women human rights defender]] |children = |spouse = | url = }}
'''Elena Eva Reynaga''' (born 1953 in [[San Salvador de Jujuy|Jujuy]]) is an Argentinian former sex worker and [[Women human rights defenders|women human rights defender]] who campaigns for the rights of sex workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cotidianomujer.org.uy/sitio/ni-mas-ni-menos/1503-el-movimiento-de-mujeres-necesita-de-todas-las-mujeres-entrevista-con-elena-reynaga|title=“El movimiento de mujeres necesita de todas las mujeres”. Entrevista con Elena Reynaga - Cotidiano Mujer|website=www.cotidianomujer.org.uy|language=es-es|access-date=2018-06-06|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608115936/http://www.cotidianomujer.org.uy/sitio/ni-mas-ni-menos/1503-el-movimiento-de-mujeres-necesita-de-todas-las-mujeres-entrevista-con-elena-reynaga|archivedate=2018-06-08|df=}}</ref> She is a founding member of [[Association of Women Sex Workers in Argentina in Action for Our Rights|Association of Women Sex Workers in Argentina]] (''Asociación de Mujeres Meretrices de la Argentina, AMMAR'') and Executive Secretary of the Network of Women Sex workers of Latina America and the Caribbean (''Red de Mujeres Trabajadoras Sexuales de Latinoamérica y Caribe, RedTraSex'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/democraciaabierta/piers-purdy-and-natalia-umansky-with-elena-reynaga/if-i-were-born-again-i-would-st|title="If I were born again, I would still be a sex worker"|date=2016-10-25|website=openDemocracy|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226065641/https://www.opendemocracy.net/democraciaabierta/piers-purdy-and-natalia-umansky-with-elena-reynaga/if-i-were-born-again-i-would-st|archivedate=2017-12-26|df=}}</ref>
== Activism == Reynaga became a sex worker at 19. After being a victim of institutional violence and experiencing imprisonment multiple times in Argentinar, she travelled to work in Spain for a time. She returned to Argentina and founded AMMAR in 1994 in response to police harassment and violence.
According to the organization, between 1996 and 2001, 41 member of AMMAR were murdered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ammar.org.ar/-Quienes-somos-.html|title=ammar.org.ar|website=www.ammar.org.ar|access-date=2018-06-04|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016135956/http://www.ammar.org.ar/-Quienes-somos-.html|archivedate=2017-10-16|df=}}</ref> AMMAR operates as a trade union and since 1995 it has been an affiliated member of the [[Argentine Workers' Central Union]] (''Central de Trabajadores de la Argentina''). AMMAR has also been part of RedTraSex since 1997; Reynaga has been its Executive Secretary since 1999. The organization works for the defence, promotion, recognition and respect for human rights of sex workers in fifteen countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.redtrasex.org/-Sobre-Nosotras-|title=RedTraSex|website=www.redtrasex.org|access-date=2018-06-04|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205234300/http://www.redtrasex.org/-Sobre-Nosotras-|archivedate=2017-12-05|df=}}</ref> Reynaga co-edited ''Un Movimiento de Tacones Altos'' (The High Heels Movement) a manual for the defense of sex workers' rights published in 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.redtrasex.org/IMG/pdf/armado-manual.pdf|title=El Movimiento de Tacones Altos|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608115936/https://www.redtrasex.org/IMG/pdf/armado-manual.pdf|archivedate=2018-06-08|df=}}</ref>
Reynaga has also campaigned on issues related to health (HIV/AIDS)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/sarah-boseley-global-health/2010/mar/25/hiv-infection-international-aid-and-development|title=Would legalising sex work help fight Aids?|last=Boseley|first=Sarah|date=2010-03-25|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909170313/http://www.theguardian.com/society/sarah-boseley-global-health/2010/mar/25/hiv-infection-international-aid-and-development|archivedate=2013-09-09|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saini|first=Anna|last2=Reynaga|first2=Elena Eva|last3=Parmanand|first3=Sharmila|last4=Grant|first4=Melissa Gira|last5=El Feki|first5=Shereen|date=2016|title=The Big QuestionTaking ControlAn Actual JobMeaningful Inclusion in the Philippines“It’s Scary for you . . . It has to be”The Law is an ass|url=https://read.dukeupress.edu/world-policy-journal/article-abstract/33/4/5/30889/The-Big-QuestionWhat-Do-Sex-Workers-Need-to-Better?redirectedFrom=fulltext|journal=World Policy Journal|language=en|volume=33|issue=4|pages=5–9|doi=10.1215/07402775-3812858|issn=0740-2775|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180602092636/https://read.dukeupress.edu/world-policy-journal/article-abstract/33/4/5/30889/The-Big-QuestionWhat-Do-Sex-Workers-Need-to-Better?redirectedFrom=fulltext|archivedate=2018-06-02|df=}}</ref> In 2008, she was the first to address the issue of sex worker's rights in a plenary session of the [[International AIDS Conference]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bliss|first=K|date=September 2008|title=XVII International AIDS Conference in Mexico City: Implications for Latin America and the Caribbean|url=|journal=Hemisphere focus, Center for strategic and international studies|volume=Volume XVI, Issue 3|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/sites/default/files/media_asset/20080724_women_aids_guide_en_0.pdf|title=All women, all rights. 2008 Delegates guide to Women and AIDS|last=Global coalition on women and AIDS|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729173302/http://www.unaids.org/sites/default/files/media_asset/20080724_women_aids_guide_en_0.pdf|archive-date=2017-07-29|dead-url=no|access-date=|df=}}</ref> where she asked for better working conditions, health care, recognition of sex work as work, and called on the audience to see sex workers not as the problem, but as "part of the solution". <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://panoslondon.panosnetwork.org/features/finally-sex-comes-to-aids-2008/|title=Finally, sex comes to AIDS 2008 {{!}} Panos London|website=panoslondon.panosnetwork.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608115937/http://panoslondon.panosnetwork.org/features/finally-sex-comes-to-aids-2008/|archivedate=2018-06-08|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scarletalliance.org.au/events/0809/mexico08/reynaga_crago/|title=- Elena Reynaga and Anna-Louise Crago, Mexico Conference Presentation, August 2008|website=www.scarletalliance.org.au|language=en|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313113723/http://www.scarletalliance.org.au/events/0809/mexico08/reynaga_crago/|archivedate=2018-03-13|df=}}</ref>
== Recognition == In 2009, the Buenos Aires legislature recognised Reynaga as "Outstanding Public Figure for the Human Rights of Women" (in Spanish “Personalidad Destacada de los Derechos Humanos de las Mujeres”).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/sociedad/3-132708-2009-10-01.html|title=Página/12 :: Sociedad :: Una distinción para Elena Reynaga|website=www.pagina12.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124031410/http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/sociedad/3-132708-2009-10-01.html|archivedate=2010-01-24|df=}}</ref> In 2014 she was recognised by the Argentinian Senate for her human rights work and leadership against discrimination and stigma, as well as the reclamation of female sex workers as workers. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cta.org.ar/elena-reynaga-fue-galardonada-por.html?rubrique5|title=Elena Reynaga fue galardonada por el Senado de la Nación Argentina|website=Central de Trabajadores de la Argentina|access-date=2018-06-04|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608115936/http://www.cta.org.ar/elena-reynaga-fue-galardonada-por.html?rubrique5|archivedate=2018-06-08|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cta.org.ar/elena-reynaga-fue-galardonada-por.html?rubrique5|title=Elena Reynaga fue galardonada por el Senado de la Nación Argentina|website=Central de Trabajadores de la Argentina|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608115936/http://www.cta.org.ar/elena-reynaga-fue-galardonada-por.html?rubrique5|archivedate=2018-06-08|df=}}</ref> In 2016 she was elected onto a UN advisory board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/democraciaabierta/piers-purdy-and-natalia-umansky-with-elena-reynaga/if-i-were-born-again-i-would-st|title="If I were born again, I would still be a sex worker"|date=2016-10-25|website=openDemocracy|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226065641/https://www.opendemocracy.net/democraciaabierta/piers-purdy-and-natalia-umansky-with-elena-reynaga/if-i-were-born-again-i-would-st|archivedate=2017-12-26|df=}}</ref>
