{{Redirect|Shaking dance|the Macedonian folk dance|Tresenica}}
A '''grooming dance''', '''grooming invitation dance''' or '''shaking dance''' is a dance performed by [[honeybees]] to initiate [[social grooming|allogrooming]]. It was first reported in 1945 by biologist Mykola H. Hadak.<ref>Haydak, M. H. (1945) The language of the honeybees. ''American Bee Journal.'' Volume 85. pp. 316—317.</ref> An increase in the frequency of the grooming dance has been observed among the bees of mite-infested colonies,<ref>Pettis, J.S., T. Pankiw. (May–June 1998) Grooming behavior by Apis mellifera L. in the presence of Acarapis woodi (Rennie) (Acari: Tarsonemidae). ''Apidologie.'' Volume 29, Issue 3. pp. 241-253.</ref> and among bees who have been dusted with small particles of chalk dust.<ref>Land, B. B., T. D. Seeley. (28 January 2004) The Grooming Invitation Dance of the Honey Bee. ''Ethology.'' Volume 110, Issue 1. pp. 1-10.</ref>
